english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of Sorim Temple
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: The Way of the Sage rises and falls through the ages, yet transforms the world in its passing. Thus Confucius, in the twilight of the Zhou, spread his teachings of benevolence and righteousness. Then came Yang, Mo, the Yellow Emperor, and Laozi in succession—strange doctrines and peculiar methods scattered like cracks across the land. By the Qin and Han, their corruptions had spread everywhere, becoming unbearable to hear. At this moment, the Buddha's teaching entered the Middle Kingdom, revealing the supreme truth in its pure essence, teaching compassion and salvation for all beings. Thus it answered the needs of the age. The philosopher Liu said, "The Buddha's doctrine does not differ from Confucius's way," and again, "The true dharma seal, used alongside the Confucian classics, shows men the path they should follow." If we unify these teachings, neither Confucianism nor Buddhism differ in their ultimate aim. Since the Jin and Song dynasties, many worthy scholars and officials have been drawn to this truth. Bai Juyi, the great Tang scholar, held the sutras in deepest reverence, practiced them throughout his life, and in his twilight years called himself the Hermit of Fragrant Mountain, establishing a community in the mountains devoted to Buddha's work—his faith was indeed profound. Now the gentleman Kim Ryung-ui of Qiantang, who venerates the Buddha's law, admires Bai Juyi's character and has long wished to establish a pure hermitage, donning monk's robes to dwell there, believing he would thus transcend worldly defilement and approach enlightenment. Is this not what is meant by living through the Buddha's law and receiving its blessing? He once said, "Rank and wealth are what all men cherish, yet I have never obtained them. But should the world employ me, I shall practice the Way; should it abandon me, I shall sit in retirement—this is my aspiration." He withdrew to Gongcheng County, where he had a dwelling and several fields. He planted hemp, cultivated grain, and his household prospered—yet nothing through dishonest means. Having devoted himself to the Buddha's law, he took charitable giving as his calling. In the northwestern corner of the county stood a temple called Sorim, established long ago by local people as a place for seeking blessings. Dense with forest and perfectly balanced between bustling and stillness, it drew noble spirits and virtuous seekers of inner cultivation. Yet centuries had passed; wind and rain had ravaged it until only broken walls and shattered eaves remained, barely sheltering from the elements. Though a few humble monks lingered, the morning incense and evening chants had ceased for centuries. Cloud-wrapped mountains and mist-shrouded waters held endless melancholy. Yet the local customs were coarse and few engaged in good works; none undertook its repair. This long grieved those of vision. Seeing the temple's decay, Kim Ryung-ui sighed deeply and swore, "I shall vow to rebuild this place as my final dwelling ground." He set forth his resolve, expending tens of thousands in silver for workers, reconstructing and renewing it, adorning it with gold and green pigment until it shone with splendor. From the fourteenth year of Dajing, sixth month, through the seventeenth year, seventh month, the work proceeded. He commissioned a new statue of Guanyin Bodhisattva, provided precious shrines, silk coverings, flowers and fruits, banners and streamers, cast bells and stone chimes, and furnished cushions, curtains, meditation seats, tables, and ritual vessels of every kind. When all was completed, he submitted his achievements to the court, requesting that fifteen hundred stones of grain be stored at the temple, with the interest used annually for offerings and the maintenance of fifteen virtuous monks in perpetual service. He hoped that through this meritorious deed, the Son of Heaven might receive the protection of all heavens and extend his lifespan in Buddha's radiant light. The throne approved, declaring it good, and commanded the provincial officials to attend the dedication ceremony. The Agama Sutra teaches, "Whoever repairs an ancient temple gains the dual blessing of Brahma." Thus all virtuous deeds and wholesome roots vowed in service to ruler and parent find no better expression than this. Truly his goodness is cause for joy. Through his example, the local customs transformed—harshness became benevolence, all came to honor the Buddha's teachings, and every traveler passing the temple joined hands in reverence. Such is the way the gentleman benefits himself and others, bringing harmony to the world. Thus we know that wherever a noble person dwells, though he hide his virtue and conceal his light, all things receive his grace—not waiting for rank and position to bear fruit. Kim Ryung-ui wished to preserve the dates of this restoration and sent someone requesting I commit it to writing. Though I demurred, I could not refuse. Thus I have set down his words in this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Way of the Sage' (聖人之道) refers to the principles of moral cultivation and governance that manifest differently through history.
  - key: ''
    value: Bai Juyi (白居易), the renowned Tang poet and official, is historically known for his later embrace of Buddhist teachings.
  - key: ''
